title A radiant pass over today's own docs, and a deeper (still inconclusive) look at the markdown rendering report
prompt Keaton plugged in the Pixel phone, reported the pixel-10a-grapheneos-setup.md file still not rendering after the earlier line-wrap fix, and asked for a radiant style pass over our recent docs.
think Went one level deeper on the rendering question than the prior turn's own diagnosis, since the line-wrap fix evidently did not resolve it -- checked specifically for stray carriage returns (\r), since my earlier control-character scan's own regex range ([\x00-\x08\x0B\x0C\x0E-\x1F]) had a real gap: it excluded \x0D (CR) entirely, sitting between the \x0C and \x0E-\x1F ranges I did check. Confirmed zero CRs present -- that specific gap in my own prior check turned out not to be the answer, though it was a real gap worth closing regardless.
think Checked three more plausible content-level causes before concluding the file itself is not the problem: literal "<" characters (a markdown renderer trying to parse embedded HTML is a classic silent-failure cause) -- none found; fence-marker balance after all edits -- still exactly two clean pairs; unmatched "**" bold-marker parity -- zero odd lines. With every content-level hypothesis now checked and ruled out, named the honest conclusion plainly rather than inventing a fifth guess: the file is genuinely valid markdown, and the persistent rendering failure is most likely a Cursor editor/preview-specific issue (cache, pane desync) rather than anything in the document's own text.
think Checked whether this jail could see the newly-plugged-in Pixel at all, out of real curiosity rather than expecting success -- no /dev/bus/usb, no lsusb output, confirming what the whole HAWM/Pixel thread has already established all session: hardware access is host-terminal-only, by the jail's own design, and nothing here changes that.
think For the radiant pass: scoped it deliberately to files actually touched today (git log --since this morning) rather than the whole tree, matching this project's own established convention for a "scoped Radiant Style sweep" (the exact phrase already used for a prior, similarly-scoped pass recorded in TASKS.md). Grepped every touched .md file for bare "but" as the fast, already-established proxy this tree uses for a Radiant self-check, deliberately leaving the .bron session logs out of the scope (internal reasoning records, not narrative prose in the same sense).
think Did not blanket-fix every "but" match found -- read each in context first and classified it by actual authorship: several hits sat inside older, pre-existing dated prose (20260714/20260715 sentences in living, accreted documents like the sameness-rune brief and two-dev-environments spec) that I did not write today, and accrete-never-break means those stay exactly as their own session wrote them. Fixed only the instances genuinely inside paragraphs I authored today, across six files, and explicitly left two more alone on purpose: a historical bullet in TASKS.md that is itself a record of a past radiant sweep (ironic to rewrite), and two legitimate hyphenated compounds ("named-but-ungranted," "honestly-but-unfixed") that are not the sentence-connective "but" the style guidance actually targets.
think Verified each fix did not change any factual claim, only the connective word or its surrounding punctuation -- read every edited sentence once more after the edit, side by side with what it said before, to confirm no meaning drifted while the voice sharpened.
obs The rendering question stays genuinely open and unresolved at the content level, honestly reported as such rather than declared fixed a second time on a guess -- worth naming plainly that two real content-level hypotheses have now been ruled out (long lines, CR/control characters/malformed markdown), and the most likely remaining explanation points outside the file entirely.
